!! # Tags for originating language

!! The following tags are used to guide conversion to IPA: loan words
!! and foreign names are usually pronounced (approximately) as in the
!! originating (majority) language. Instead of trying to identify the
!! correct pronunciation based on phonotactics (orthotactics actually),
!! we tag all words that can't be correctly transcribed using the SME
!! transcriber with source language codes. Once tagged, it is possible
!! to split the lexical transducer in smaller ones according to langu-
!! age, and apply different IPA conversion to each of them.
!!
!! The principle of tagging is that we only tag to the extent needed,
!! and following a priority:
!! 1. any untagged word is pronounced with SME orthographic conventions
!! 1. NNO and NOB have identical pronunciation, NNO is only used if
!!   different in spelling from NOB
!! 1. SWE has mostly the same pronunciation as NOB, and is only used
!!   if different in spelling from NOB
!! 1. Occasionally even SME (the default) may be tagged, to block other
!!   languages from being specified, mainly during semi-automatic
!!   language tagging sessions
!!
!! All in all, we want to get as much correctly transcribed to IPA
!! with as little work as possible. On the other hand, if more words
!! are tagged than strictly needed, this should pose no problem as
!! long as the IPA conversion is correct - at least some words will
!! get the same pronunciation whether read as SME or NOB/NNO/SWE.

+OLang/CHV !!‚Čą * **@CODE@** = Chuvash
+OLang/MDF !!‚Čą * **@CODE@** = Moksha
+OLang/MYV !!‚Čą * **@CODE@** = Erzya
+OLang/RUS !!‚Čą * **@CODE@** = Russian
+OLang/TAT !!‚Čą * **@CODE@** = Tatar


!! Morphophonology
!  ---------------
!! To represent phonologic variations in word forms we use the following
!! symbols in the lexicon files:
 %{–ė–ę–ô%}	!!= @CODE@ phasing out –ę2, eg –ļ—É–Ĺ–ī–į–ľ—Ā:–ļ—É–Ĺ–ī–į–Ļ
 %{–ē–ě√ė%}	!!= @CODE@ morphemes requiring a preceding vowel; also –Ņ–ł–Ĺ–≥–Ķ
 %{–ē–ě%} 	!!= @CODE@ —Ā–Ķ–Ľ—Ć–ľ–Ķ
 %{–ē√ė%}	!!= @CODE@ –ļ–Ķ—á–Ķ
 %{–ź–Į%} 	!!= @CODE@ –ź2 in –ļ—É–Ĺ–ī–į–ľ—Ā:–ļ—É–Ĺ–ī–į–Ĺ
 %{–í–ė–£%}        !!= @CODE@ lative
 %{–•%}		!!= @CODE@ This usually precedes the plural marker
 %{–ö–Ę%}		!!= @CODE@ used in imperative and connegative
 %{–¨√ė%}	!!= @CODE@ after imperative Sg2
 %{DIM%}	!!= @CODE@ This will be for diminutive initial consonant

!! 2016-03-12
%^–ź2–ě		!!= @CODE@ used with final –į in –Ņ—É–Ľ–į 

 –ź2 	!!= @CODE@ –ź2:–į –ź2:—Ź
 %{–≤–≥–ļ%} 	!!= @CODE@ %{–≤–≥–ļ%}:–≥ %{–≤–≥–ļ%}:–≤ %{–≤–≥–ļ%}:–ļ
 %{–≥–ļ%}	!!= @CODE@ clitic in ``` %{–≥–ļ%} %{–ź–ē%} ```
 –ö1 	!!= @CODE@ –ö1:–ļ –ö1:—ā
%{–ź–ē√ė%}	!!= @CODE@  ConNeg with –į—ą–Ķ–Ĺ—Ć, —ā—Ź—ā, –į—Ą–ĺ–Ľ—Ć
%{–ź–ě%}	!!= @CODE@  –Ņ—É–Ľ–į stem
%{–ź–ě√ė%}	!!= @CODE@  –ĺ—Ą—ā–į stem
%{–ź–ē%}	!!= @CODE@ prolative
 –•1 	!!= @CODE@ –•1:—Ö –•1:0
 –¨2 	!!= @CODE@ –¨2:—Ć –¨2:0
%{—ä√ė%}        !!= @CODE@ This will represent schwa in first syllable
! –™2	occurs in first syllable and is not written in the Moksha orthography, 

!! in ped realized as hard sign

!! And following triggers to control variation
%^RmVow 	!!= * @CODE@ for removing vowels
%^–¨2ZERO	!!= @CODE@ removes soft sign before vowel or other combination
%^–¨KEEP		!!= @CODE@ retains soft sign, breaks pattern for removal —ą—Ź—Ź—Ä—Ć–Ĺ—Ź
%^–™2PED		!!= @CODE@ brings out hard sign, which is otherwise automatically removed
%^–ē2–ě		!!= @CODE@ Change stem-final vowel —Ā–Ķ–ľ–Ī–Ķ:—Ā–Ķ–ľ–Ī–ĺ—Ā—Ć
%^–ē2–ź		!!= @CODE@ Change stem-final vowel –ľ–Ķ–Ľ—Ć–≥–Ķ:–ľ–Ķ–Ľ—Ć–≥–į–Ĺ–∑–į
%^–Į2–ź		!!= @CODE@ Change stem-final vowel —Ä—Ć–≤—Ź:—Ä—Ć–≤–į–Ĺ—Ü
%^–ź2–ē		!!= @CODE@ Change stem-final vowel –ľ–ĺ–ļ—ą–į:–ľ–ĺ–ļ—ą–Ķ—Ā—Ć
%^–ē2–Į		!!= @CODE@ Change word-final vowel for dialect —ā—É–≤–ĺ—ā–Ĺ–Ķ > —ā—É–≤–ĺ—ā–Ĺ—Ź
%^Devoice	!!= @CODE@ for devoicing –ł–∑—Ć:–ł—Ā—ā—Ć
%^PXSG1		!!= @CODE@ –ļ—Ź–ī–Ĺ–Ķ, —Ź—Ä–ľ–į–ļ–ĺ–Ĺ–Ķ –Ĺ–Ķ vs %{–ē–ě√ė%}–Ĺ–Ķ
%^CnsSt		!!= @CODE@ —É–Ľ–Ķ–ľ—Ā:—É–Ľ—Ć%^CnsSt%>%{–ź–ē√ė%}	
%^Glide		!!= @CODE@ –Ę–ĺ–Ľ—Ā—ā–ĺ–Ļ:–Ę–ĺ–Ľ—Ā—ā–ĺ–Ļ%^Glide%>–Ĺ—Ć

